column1: 161013;instagram;2018-12-23 00:00:38;FALSE;"this survivor story was submitted to the project by @justwantloveandlight in south africa. i was particularly struck by her usage of the phrase â€œrite of passage.â€ a rite of passage is *supposed* to be a significant moment marking a milestone or accomplishment in someoneâ€™s life- a joyful moment
column2: like the high school graduation she had been celebrating with friends the night of her attack. it is not supposed to be a violent and traumatic personal violation- like what this man did to her at the music festival she attended that weekend. but stories like this one are so common that it almost seems like sexual assault and rape are hidden
column4: insidious rites of passage for many women. like some ceremony marking adulthood
column5: survivors are expected to solemnly and silently bear the weight of this trauma
column6: with little believablilty thrown our way
column7: and with little regard or accountability held to our attackers. that is what we are working to change. â€¢

column2: she reached out to me and told me that she had never told anyone what had happened to her and that it was really scary to write it all down- but even more than that
column3: it was liberating to get it out of her system. iâ€™ve said it before
column4: and iâ€™ll say it again- there is such power in speaking your truth. burying these stories and carrying them alone is too heavy a weight for any one person to bear- no one should have to go through this alone. thank you
column6: for submitting your story. i hear you
column7: and i believe you. i also want you to know that what was stolen from you is still yours to consensually and lovingly give to someone one day- whomever that person may be
column8: as long as you deem them worthy. you are so valuable

column1: the #metoo movement has begun to reveal just how many people have been affected by an often-ignored and unfortunately all-too-common culture of sexual entitlement and violence. survivors are standing up
column3: and getting the world to listen. this issue of the london reader confronts this challenging topic through the stories of pain and survival of the authors

column1: #metoo: stories of survival features a guest foreword by christina dalcher
column2: author of the best-selling novel vox
column3: and an interview with the award-winning novelist emma donoghue
column4: author of the man booker-shortlisted novel room
column5: and the oscar-nominated screenplay based on it.

column1: this is a topic for which it is important to listen
column2: to hold space for the speakers
column3: and to give a platform for their voices. we readers should be listening. it is their stories that need to be heard. this issue is dedicated to them.  find out more at www.londonreader.uk/metoo

column1: 161151;instagram;2018-12-23 06:31:12;FALSE;"this year a few colleueges and i created an online publication. although our magazine began as an assignment for school
column2: it has since become something more. the intent of the magazine is to inspire women to pursue their careers goals despite all of the obstacles that may be present. our focus is to highlight women in both conventional and unconventional careers. the journey to this collaboration was not easy. during the creation of our documentary 3 out of the 5 of us were inolved in a pretty bad car accident that could have killed us. i say all that to say; life is too short and the goals that you have (no matter how ridiculous they may seem) are valid and the pursuit of these goals are worth it. i'm never fully confident in anything that i do in all honesty
column3: and i have anxiety right before i do any that scares me (which is low key everything lol). but i would hate myself if i didnt at least give it a try. anyways

column1: 161242;instagram;2018-12-23 10:35:02;FALSE;"provocative floral images. pieces from my 2018 personal project challenge for @photo_club_pdx

column2: often sublimely so. sex can open us to ridicule
column3: or to enlightenment. nothing about sex is for sure
column4: except that it's consequential. ~robert w. fuller ph.d

column1: this project began innocently enough as i was exploring heavy
column2: supple baskets of fragrant and exotic flowers
column3: wet and dripping on my front porch after their nightly watering
column4: while i was experimenting with unconventional light sources and angles. it wasn't until later as i was processing the images that i realized how the flora often resemble genitalia. it wasn't long before all i could see were sexual attributes in all of my floral images.

column1: sexuality is the pinnacle of taboo topics while it is also the most pervasive force in nature and in human behavior. sexuality is everywhere. we see it
column5: and make decisions based upon it every day. to be human is to be sexual and to be sexual is to be human.

column7: and damaging facet as well. the recent #metoo movement is a prime example of the consequences wrought upon society when our sexuality as a human condition is ignored and shamed.

column1: my hope is that these images will bring thoughts of sexuality to the forefront of the viewer's mind endeavoring to normalize a topic that continues to be awkward and forbidden
column2: even in our more modern and liberal society.

column1: 161487;instagram;2018-12-23 18:04:41;FALSE;"hey you. itâ€™s day 4 of eoiâ€™s 12 days of giving!

column2: we give thanks to sex education for giving young people the very building blocks of sexual assault prevention.

we honor #metoo for what it has provided survivors of sexual abuse and assault: a collective movement and space to speak their stories and confront their abusers. this work is critical for healing and shifting the cultural norm of silence and acceptance around abuse and assault.

we also know that comprehensive sex education helps prevent such abuse by teaching young people about consent: how to demand it for themselves and ask for it from others. no other curriculum teaches this to teens.

if you need a refresher on the project or you missed my previous posts about it before hereâ€™s some info. â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸ my latest project is called â€œ#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.â€

the book will be a collection of true story experiences written in womenâ€™s own words. these poems and stories will chronicle the crimes and the effects that the experiences had on each woman. ğŸ”œ stories and poems will be accepted until december 31

all stories/poems will be listed as anonymous submissions. â¡ï¸the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well. ğŸ”´ through writing about my own experiences i have found peace and strength.

column4: we don't teach our children how to say no. we teach them to say yes to us even when they don't want to (my child will make me regret this but this is far more important). we need to teach our children to say no and we need them to practice it a lot before they can have the courage to say it in a place of vulnerability.

column1: i found an excellent article on this at everydayfeminism.com. i googled
column2: ""practice saying no to sex."" this is not just for girls either. our boys need to know how to say no too. also google ""tea consent"" for a humorous yet powerful message about consent on  youtube.

column1: like many people i have been in a situation where i said no but didn't maintain my resolve
column2: or i stayed quiet terrified to speak. i have allowed myself to stay quiet even though i was screaming inside. then i felt shame for not using my voice and allowing things to happen to me i wasn't okay with. i wasn't ever taught to say no though. i was taught to do as i was told. listening and respecting your parents is one thing but i think that concept was taught in a way that didn't allow me to be able to say no when i needed to. this needs to change. we need to teach our children not only to say no but also how to stand firm
column3: walk away and respect themselves. my greatest fear is that our children will go through what so many of us have: sexual assault or rape. we need to give them the tools to prevent this because it's so common it's sickening. please take the time to read the article i mentioned. it talks about tools we can use for ourselves and our children. stay safe and practice saying no!

column1: there are moments you think you know it all and bam one incident breaks the myth and puts you in front of the reality. #metoo was one such movement for me! here i was sitting comfortably thinking that equality has arrived seeing my female colleagues getting equal responsibility and pay for the same work but that isn't enough (if it's there).

the movement shook me hard and made me realise that we as men need to be more respectful towards women not only the ones we work with but who're around us. what i liked about it the most was that it put some accountability on men about their actions and in future they'll think twice before doing something this heinous. of course the film fraternity was in lime light but the effect it had could be felt everywhere around you. we need to credit women and laud them for coming out and telling their stories to the world which some are afraid to tell even their loved ones. hope it will make more men accountable and makes every environment a comfortable one for women in 2019!"" - @tellmestories
